SIMPLE: pledge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pledge
<hw>Pledge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>plege</ets>,
<ets>pleige</ets>, pledge, guaranty, LL. <ets>plegium</ets>,
<ets>plivium</ets>; akin to OF. <ets>plevir</ets> to bail, guaranty,
perhaps fr. L. <ets>praebere</ets> to proffer, offer (<ets>sc.</ets>
<ets>fidem</ets> a trust, a promise of security), but cf. also E.
<ets>play</ets>. ⟦root⟧28. Cf. <er>Prebend</er>,
<er>Replevin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The transfer
of possession of personal property from a debtor to a creditor as
security for a debt or engagement; also, the contract created between
the debtor and creditor by a thing being so delivered or deposited,
forming a species of bailment; also, that which is so delivered or
deposited; something put in pawn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Pledge</xex> is ordinarily confined to personal
property; the title or ownership does not pass by it; possession is
essential to it. In all these points it differs from a mortgage [see
<er>Mortgage</er>]; and in the last, from the <xex>hypotheca</xex> of
the Roman law. See <er>Hypotheca</er>.</note> <rj><au>Story.
Kent.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Old Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A person who undertook, or
became responsible, for another; a bail; a surety; a hostage.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧I am Grumio's <xex>pledge</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hypothecation without transfer of
possession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything given or considered as a security for the
performance of an act; a guarantee; <as>as, mutual interest is the best
<ex>pledge</ex> for the performance of treaties</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧That
voice, their liveliest <xex>pledge</xex> of hope.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A promise or agreement by which one binds one's self
to do, or to refrain from doing, something; especially, a solemn promise
in writing to refrain from using intoxicating liquors or the like;
<as>as, to sign the <ex>pledge</ex>; the mayor had made no
<ex>pledges</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- esp. in "take the pledge" -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A sentiment to which assent is given by drinking
one's health; a toast; a health.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dead pledge</b></col>. <ety>[A translation of
<er>LL</er>. <ets>mortuum vadium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>A
mortgage. See <er>Mortgage</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Living
pledge</b></col>. <ety>[A translation of LL. <ets>vivum
vadium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>The conveyance of an estate to
another for money borrowed, to be held by him until the debt is paid out
of the rents and profits.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold in pledge</b></col>,
<cd>to keep as security.</cd> -- <col><b>To put in pledge</b></col>,
<cd>to pawn; to give as security.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Earnest</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pledge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pledge
<hw>Pledge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pledged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pledging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>pleiger</ets> to
give security. See <er>Pledge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To deposit, as a chattel, in pledge or pawn; to leave in possession
of another as security; <as>as, <ex>to pledge</ex> one's
watch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give or pass as a security; to guarantee; to
engage; to plight; <as>as, to <ex>pledge</ex> one's word and
honor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We mutually <qex>pledge</qex> to each other our lives, our
fortunes, and our sacred honor.</q> <rj><qau>The Declaration of
Independence.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To secure performance of, as by a pledge.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>pledge</qex> my vow, I give my hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bind or engage by promise or declaration; to
engage solemnly; <as>as, to <ex>pledge</ex> one's self</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To invite another to drink, by drinking of the cup
first, and then handing it to him, as a pledge of good will; hence, to
drink the health of; to toast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Pledge</qex> me, my friend, and drink till thou be'st
wise.</q> <rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pledgee</ent>⟦br⟧
